This allows yas3fs to work with minimal IAM policies, per:

http://stackoverflow.com/questions/11478752/with-the-boto-library-can-i-avoid-granting-list-permissions-on-a-base-bucket-in

e.g.

```json
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Sid": "Stmt1422406089000",
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": [
        "s3:ListBucket"
      ],
      "Resource": [
        "arn:aws:s3:::bucket.example.com"
      ],
      "Condition": {
        "StringLike": {
          "s3:prefix": "prefix/*"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "Effect":"Allow",
      "Action":[
        "s3:GetObject"
      ],
      "Resource":[
        "arn:aws:s3:::bucket.example.com/prefix/*"
      ]
    }
  ]
}
```

This handles the issues raised in #9 and #10.

Very simply, it allows passing keyword arguments to `frontmatter.dump` and `frontmatter.dumps`, which will then be forwarded to `yaml.dump`. By default, `frontmatter.dumps` sets `Dumper` to `yaml.SafeDumper` (or its C-variant), so current usage should work as expected.

